The RISCTP Theorem Proving Interface
====================================
https://www.risc.jku.at/research/formal/software/RISCTP

The RISCTP theorem proving interface consists of a language for specifying proof
problems and of an associated software for solving these problems. The RISCTP
language is a typed variant of first-order logic whose level of abstraction is
between that of higher level formal specification languages (such as the
language of the RISCAL model checker) and lower level theorem proving languages
(such as the language SMT-LIB supported by various satisfiability modulo
theories solvers and theorem provers such as Z3, cvc5, or Vampire). Thus the
RISCTP language can serve as an intermediate layer that simplifies the
connection of specification and verification systems to theorem provers; in
fact, it was developed to equip the RISCAL model checker with theorem proving
capabilities.

The RISCTP software is implemented in Java with an API that enables the
implementation of such connections; however, RISCTP also provides a text-based
frontend and a web-based graphical user interface that allow its use as a
theorem prover on its own. RISCTP provides a backend that translates a proving
problem into SMT-LIB and solves it by the "black box" application of an external
SMT solver. Furthermore, RISCTP implements two internal provers for first-order
logic with equality (based on the proof calculi of MESON (model-elimination,
subgoal-oriented), and resolution/superposition, respectively) and the
possibility to inspect successful proofs as well as failed proof attempts. These
provers also supports reasoning in the theories of integers, arrays/maps,
tuples, and algebraic datatypes, via a corresponding axiomatization, and/or the
application of an external SMT solver.

Please send bug reports to the main author of this software:

  Wolfgang Schreiner <Wolfgang.Schreiner@risc.jku.at>
